# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The problem requires us to compress the input character array in place using a given algorithm. We need to count the consecutive groups of identical characters and replace them with a character followed by its count. For example, `aaa` should become `a3`. If a group has only one character, we do not add any count. If a group has a count greater than or equal to 10, we split it into multiple characters. We can use two pointers to keep track of the characters to be replaced and their counts.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We can use two pointers `i` and `j` to traverse the input array. We initialize both pointers
to 0. We iterate over the input array using `j` pointer until `j` reaches the end of the array.
We keep track of the count of consecutive identical characters using a variable `count`.
When `chars[j]` is not equal to `chars[j-1]`, we add `chars[i]` to the compressed array.
If `count` is greater than 1, we convert it to a string and add it to the compressed array. We
then move the `i` pointer to the next position and reset the `count` to 1. We continue this
process until we reach the end of the input array. Finally, we return the length of thecompressed array.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$, where n is the length of the input array. We traverse the array only once.

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$, since we are performing the compression in place and using a constant amount of extra space.



